<TITLE> Measles kills at least 20 children in Nigeria </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MJIMTILO, Nigeria, June 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - At least 20 children have died from a measles outbreak in a village in northeastern Nigeria, residents and health officials said on Tuesday. About 50 other children are being treated for the virus, which is highly contagious and frequently kills children in poor countries, authorities said. "We have received reports of more than 20 people killed by measles and airborne diseases," said Abdulrahman Usman, director of disease control at the health ministry in Borno state. "We have despatched our staff to reinforce health workers in the area to bring the situation under control," he added. Residents of Mjimtilo, a grass hut village about 3 miles (5 km) outside the Borno state capital, said the epidemic took them by surprise. "I never knew that measles could be so devastating. I lost two children to the disease and my neighbours have equally lost their children," said Musa Ahmadu. "We are at a loss as to what to do. You can see some of neighbours are fleeing the village," he added. Usman said the government was trying to cordon off the village to stop the spread of the disease. Measles is an air-borne virus which has been largely wiped out in many rich nations because of vaccinations, but remains a big killer of children in the poor world, particularly when combined with malnutrition. Symptoms include coughing, a runny nose and slight fever in the first stage, then a red rash that spreads over the body and lasts for about five days. Complications can include pneumonia, middle ear infections, swelling of the brain and seizur
